top.value: Taught by members of the Interpeace international Advisory Team, the course aims to consciously and creatively increase the advisory capacities of mid- to senior-level professionals from the humanitarian, development, stabilization, peacebuilding and human rights sectors, so as to enhance the participants' effectiveness in supporting locally led efforts fostering sustainable peace. This 2020 edition accepted participants from across the globe and was held online.

Exploratory phase for the design of a longer-term health and peace programme, to be jointly developed between Interpeace and the World Health Organization (WHO) Country Office in Ukraine. The objective of the initial exploratory phase was for Interpeace's Peace Responsiveness Team to support and assist the World Health Organization (WHO) Country Office in Ukraine to design and prepare for a multi-stakeholder consultation process on health related matters in the context of the COVID-19 response.
Integration of approaches that benefit peace, taking into account gender and youth dimensions. Assess the impact of COVID-19 on the local security dynamics.

Interpeace is part of the ERMES III consortium, upon which the European Union calls to provide assistance to conflict parties, third party mediators and groups participating in inclusive peace processes, in the context of local, national or international armed conflicts, or for preventive purposes. The Interpeace Advisory Team (IPAT) provides on-demand expertise through this mecanism.

In view of the risk of manipulation of youth in this sense, and of the “Youth, Peace and Security (YPS)” agenda, the project targets young leaders, boys and girls, who can contribute and are already leading preventive efforts in two urban communes of Abidjan. The project is innovative in that it approaches young people not as beneficiaries or mere "participants", but as leaders of initiatives to prevent political violence.

Le projet s’exécutera dans les provinces du Kasai, Kasai central, Mai Ndombe et dans la ville de Kinshasa. Il vise à renforcer la collaboration entre les acteurs de la société civile et les dirigeants en promouvant une gouvernance inclusive et participative. Durée de 4 ans, financement SIDA.

It is a four-year programme (2021-2025), which specifically aims at increasing the availability of inclusively developed and locally informed transitional justice processes in Somaliland that significantly contribute to existing efforts on social cohesion and governance. The Transitional Justice Programme will be implemented by a Consortium comprised of Interpeace, the lead Agency, in partnership with Berghof Foundation and MediaINK.

Reinforcing community capacity for social cohesion and reconciliation through societal trauma healing in Bugesera District. It  will build on the Government’s prior work in developing a decentralized and integrated mental  health  infrastructure,which  is  one  of  the  best  in  sub-Sahara  Africa,  but complimented with an existing  societal  trauma  healing  approachdeveloped  by  Interpeace  and  Never  Again  Rwanda (NAR) which  combines  psychosocial  support  group  therapy  and  group-based  skills  training  programmes.The partnership  between  the  Ministry  of  Health,  Interpeace,  NAR, the  Rwanda  Prisoner  Fellowship and  a relevant women’s organisation will  allow  for  a  programme  that  can  operate  at  the  scale  necessary  to address societal trauma and social cohesion issues identified through various studies.
